Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers enlivened the desire to penetrate within Turkey.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps into Asia, is one of the most interesting relics of the disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-renaissance style.
At least this is what the guides say.
The building is set to stand at the end of the platforms and leads in front of two towers, one for each corner, looking like a typical German city.
The stone is dirty.
The building in its complex is a little decadent.
But once the vaulted locker has been passed, there is no doubt about what was the greatness of the company that this was the most western door.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Bagdad Corporation.
Germany, a "latecomer" in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that was cured up to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond what is today Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Due to its isolation from the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell below
British rule and when the forces advanced in Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was bad for the Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 a munitions train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources commented that it was sabotage.
Since then the station has fallen and remained on the edge of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to expand its diplomatic horizons.
The Justice and Development Party that is in government - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a new partnership policy.
The Turkish Government has excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To evaluate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I got into a letter and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, expert in foreign policy, Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kinikilioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a journey of shocks, which produced the cadence of the old world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - a new city, designed to govern a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamic roots, represents a paradigmatic change in Turkish consensus
which has raised some suspicions in the West and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium commercial centers built and "power pastries" where middle class managers in business suits - men and women - meet at the first hour of the morning to agree/make business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician of almost any party in Europe.
Dress, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey in its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly," she tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in its relations with its interior.
Today you have to look both east and west at the same time.
It's not a case if it's not to one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask him, "Could Turkey be forced to choose?"
"Turkey," he answers, "don't want to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone I spoke to so far had recited to me almost by memory: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East but with the Caucasus region, and with the whole Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically mount those railway lines that open the world towards East Asia and the Middle East.
Again at Hydarpasha station, after a second night without sleeping, my thought returns to the two German lords, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How much would you have been surprised to know that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East would, in large part, be in Turkey's hands today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So there is not much doubt in which continent this fascinating country must be claimed.
