Bee car avoiding collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for the prevention of Nissan accidents, this time, the nature, in particular, of bees has been inspired.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C that is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Centre have developed this little robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C is presented as an expansion of the Security Shield of four Nissan areas.
This robot intends to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions of brand vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space in oval form that is very similar to the Nissan Security Shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bee, able to see with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, which allows you to fly continuously within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects the obstacles that are up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees before BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to a microboard processor which immediately results in collision prevention.
"At the moment you detect an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right or larger angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and main engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot drift up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to prevent collisions by the small robot.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about memory gigs, not even megas."
This is the first step to develop new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan vaticine will introduce into the series cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the way.
