The Governments of the Netherlands nationalize part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalisation of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis which is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the US market: the three countries will in total support EUR 11.2 billion for this financial and insurance institution which also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the President of the European Central Bank and the Head of Economic Competition of the European Commission.
The Fortis Bank is the first to have experienced the crisis in the euro area in the context of the international financial crisis which has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so decisions taken with regard to the Bank can be considered as precedents in some sense.
According to the decision taken in the early hours of Sunday, the three States will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will surely sell a part of its business, including especially the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
The actions of the Fortis began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company's shares only decreased by 12 percent on Friday, and this is the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares decreased by more than two thirds.
Observing the current stock prices, the total value of the group's capital on the market is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management charged the sudden fall of Fortis' actions to the insecurity of the US market in relation to the approval of the US package plan of $700 billion.
On Monday the shares already showed a slight increase.
On Friday they appointed Filip Dierckx as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also looked for private investors, but so far no one has given a specific offer.
The Belgian government had already ensured that investors did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank's clients so far there has been no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
