In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when they see the data on the purchase of medicine, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy experts fear that the personal data market will be made uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which are linked to the use of the recipe data in all cases to the approval of the given person.
The same must be in independent hands, because if not, "we trust the fox chicken" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescription follow-up program.
Insurance companies rely on the price of insurance and the amount of compensation for the customer's health status and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the customer to medical control and signed with him the contract already knowing the result of the control.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer's identification number he easily gets the list of medicines purchased in the last and a half year and the program itself draws the conclusion about the client's illness and health status.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of tablets to reduce cholesterol, it indicates that the blood fat level is nearly incurably high, so it is immediately included in a higher risk category.
There are a number of versions of the programme, some of them even set a risk number, so the insurance company, in addition to the administration, has only something to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is, for example, that some medications are multi-use, for example, certain substances serve both to treat headache and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk increase factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, request the patient's approval.
The authorities are already forcing them to do this, although they have not received a fine for the negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also developed the results of the laboratory exams and combining them with the drug consumption data obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
The bill that gives the authority to control companies specializing in the provision of personal data is now before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he has therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the supply of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
